---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import InterventionDesigner from '../components/InterventionDesigner.tsx';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Step 4: Design" step={4} prev={`${base}3-qualify/`} next={`${base}5-bound/`}>
  <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto py-10 px-4 landing-content">

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h1>Design the intervention</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">You have a qualified workflow. Now figure out what to actually build and test.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>What this step is about</h2>

      <p>
        You have a workflow with steps, and you know it is worth piloting. The question now is: what does the intervention actually look like? Not "apply AI to step 4" but "how does the work change, what does AI handle, what stays with people, and how do they connect?"
      </p>

      <p>
        Most real interventions are a mix. A single workflow step might involve something deterministic (a calculation, a format conversion), something generative (drafting text, adjusting tone) and something that needs a person (reviewing, approving, making a judgement call). The goal here is to look at each step and figure out that mix.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>The mix within every step</h2>

      <p>
        Every step in a workflow contains a mix. Some parts are predictable and rule-based, like a calculator: same input, same output. Some parts need language, synthesis or pattern recognition. Some parts need human judgement, accountability or creative direction. Most steps are not purely one thing.
      </p>

      <p>
        AI can play a role across all of these. It can support creative work by generating options for a person to shape. It can supplement judgement by surfacing patterns a human might miss. It can handle routine language tasks like adapting text for different formats. And some things don't need AI at all: a spreadsheet formula or a template does the job without the unpredictability.
      </p>

      <p>
        The question is not "is this a human step or an AI step?" It is "within this step, what does each part need, and who is accountable for the outcome?" Where AI generates something that looks like a fact, someone needs to verify it. Where AI drafts something creative, someone needs to judge it. Where a calculation needs to be exact, use deterministic logic, not a language model.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>When AI is involved, what kind?</h2>

      <p>
        Not all AI is the same. Different approaches have fundamentally different capabilities, limitations and risk profiles. This matters because it determines what can go wrong and what controls you need.
      </p>

      <p>
        These are different technologies, not different uses of the same tool. An LLM can be asked to "follow rules" but that is not the same as a rules engine. A rules engine is deterministic: given the same input, it always produces the same output. An LLM following instructions is probabilistic: it might get it right most of the time but it can hallucinate, misinterpret or drift. <a href={`${base}resources/#ai-paradigms`}>Read more about the differences</a>.
      </p>

      <details class="paradigm-overview">
        <summary>Follow set rules</summary>
        <div class="paradigm-detail">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Deterministic logic. If X then Y. Spreadsheet formulas, workflow automation, business rules engines. Not really AI, but often the right answer.</p>
          <p><strong>Use when:</strong> The logic is clear and stable. Routing, validation, formatting, calculations.</p>
          <p><strong>Risks:</strong> Rigid. Breaks on edge cases. But predictable and auditable.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="paradigm-overview">
        <summary>Find answers in existing documents (RAG)</summary>
        <div class="paradigm-detail">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> An AI that <a href="https://snorkel.ai/blog/which-is-better-retrieval-augmentation-rag-or-fine-tuning-both/">retrieves information from a knowledge base</a> before generating a response. Grounds output in actual sources.</p>
          <p><strong>Use when:</strong> People need to find and synthesise information from internal documents, support tickets, policies.</p>
          <p><strong>Risks:</strong> Source quality determines output quality. Access control is critical: who should see what. <a href="https://casmi.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2024/the-hallucination-problem-a-feature-not-a-bug.html">Citation does not guarantee correctness</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="paradigm-overview">
        <summary>Draft, summarise or explain (LLM as copilot)</summary>
        <div class="paradigm-detail">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> A language model that supports a human. It drafts, summarises, explains or suggests. The human makes the final call.</p>
          <p><strong>Use when:</strong> Text-heavy work where a person is needed but the first draft or summary could be automated.</p>
          <p><strong>Risks:</strong> <a href="https://casmi.northwestern.edu/news/articles/2024/the-hallucination-problem-a-feature-not-a-bug.html">Hallucination</a> (plausible but wrong output). <a href="https://ai-analytics.wharton.upenn.edu/generative-ai-labs/research-and-technical-reports/tech-report-prompt-engineering-is-complicated-and-contingent">Prompt sensitivity</a>. Inconsistency across runs. The model's <a href="https://promptrevolution.poltextlab.com/understanding-knowledge-cut-offs-in-genai-models/">knowledge has a cut-off date</a> and <a href="https://www.coursera.org/articles/context-window">a limited context window</a>.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="paradigm-overview">
        <summary>Classify, score or predict (Machine learning)</summary>
        <div class="paradigm-detail">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> Trained models that learn patterns from historical data. Classification, scoring, anomaly detection, forecasting.</p>
          <p><strong>Use when:</strong> You have structured data and need pattern recognition at scale. Lead scoring, spam filtering, demand forecasting.</p>
          <p><strong>Risks:</strong> <a href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41586-024-07856-5">Bias in training data</a>. Data drift over time. Decisions can be hard to explain.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="paradigm-overview">
        <summary>Take actions across multiple steps (LLM as agent)</summary>
        <div class="paradigm-detail">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> An LLM that acts autonomously: calling tools, making API requests, executing multi-step workflows. The human sets the goal, the AI figures out the steps.</p>
          <p><strong>Use when:</strong> Multi-step tasks with clear success criteria where the steps are routine but the orchestration is complex.</p>
          <p><strong>Risks:</strong> Highest risk paradigm. Loss of control, scope creep, compounding errors across steps. Needs strong boundaries and monitoring.</p>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="paradigm-overview">
        <summary>Combine calculations with generated text (Hybrid)</summary>
        <div class="paradigm-detail">
          <p><strong>What it is:</strong> A system where the critical logic is deterministic (rules, calculations) and AI handles the language-rich parts (narrative, summaries, signals). Think financial reporting: the numbers are calculated, the commentary is generated.</p>
          <p><strong>Use when:</strong> Accuracy matters for some parts and fluency matters for others. The boundary between them must be enforced.</p>
          <p><strong>Risks:</strong> Architectural complexity. If the boundary between deterministic and generative is not enforced, AI-generated numbers can look like calculated ones.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>

    <div class="divider"></div>

    <div class="mb-10">
      <h2>Design your intervention</h2>

      <p>
        Below are the workflow steps you defined earlier. For each step, break down the work: what part is human, what part is deterministic and what part could involve AI. If AI is involved, pick the approach that fits.
      </p>

      <p>
        Not every step needs to change. Some steps are already fine as they are. The goal is to identify the 2-4 steps where an intervention would make the biggest difference and design what that intervention looks like.
      </p>

      <InterventionDesigner client:load />
    </div>

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .landing-content .subtitle {
    color: var(--text-light);
    font-size: 15px;
  }

  .paradigm-overview {
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-radius: 8px;
    background: var(--bg-card);
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
  }

  .paradigm-overview summary {
    padding: 0.875rem 1.25rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    font-size: 14px;
    cursor: pointer;
    list-style: none;
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: space-between;
  }

  .paradigm-overview summary::after {
    content: '+';
    font-size: 1.25rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-weight: 400;
  }

  .paradigm-overview[open] summary::after {
    content: '\2212';
  }

  .paradigm-overview summary::-webkit-details-marker {
    display: none;
  }

  .paradigm-detail {
    padding: 0 1.25rem 1.25rem;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    padding-top: 1rem;
  }

  .paradigm-detail p {
    font-size: 14px;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .paradigm-detail p + p {
    margin-top: 0.75em;
  }
</style>
